posts: [["I'm happy to share a great news. Our paper was not only accepted at CVPR 2023 but was also selected as an award candidate among 9000+ submissions! This is such an honor, I'm grateful to the committee for appreciating our work.If you attend the conference this June don't miss our talk. We invented an elegant continuous representation of neural networks which we call Integral Neural Networks.Here is the full list of accepted papers:https://lnkd.in/dVamG3PM #cvpr2023 #neuralnetworks", '51'], ["Surprisingly, Switzerland decided to ease the issuance of work permits for non-EU citizens a few days ago. FYI, I hold a PhD degree from Swiss university (EPFL) which should make things even easier.I would also highly appreciate if anyone could refer me. This whole cold approach of applying through LinkedIn doesn't really work well according to career consultants (which is shameless but true). Networking is the way to go. Good luck to everyone who is considering Swiss job market too.", '399'], ['Hi everyone - I am looking for a new role and would appreciate your support. name: Aleksandr Mironov

posts: [["A little over a year ago, I was completely amazed by the presentation of dall-e and text-to-image models in general. At that moment, the quality of the generated images was astounding; at one point, it mistakenly seemed that this was the peak of generative networks in the field of images (little did we knew haha). And now we can see how text-to-video models develop (for instance the newest Gen2 model by Runway), only a year ago we could only dream about such a result.Check this thead: https://lnkd.in/du2eQ8XBSometimes individual frames may look a little creepy, but it is already clear that in the (near?) future the generation of video by text promts will become a reality. Who knows, maybe we'll finally see a decent remake of the last season of Game of Thrones? üê≤", '5'], ['The recent success of ChatGPT has been a result of its advanced language capabilities and natural conversational style. With its ability to understand complex questions and provide accurate responses, ChatGPT has become a popular tool for a wide range of applications, from customer service to educational purposes.Many large tech companies have attempted to replicate the success of ChatGPT with their own language models, but few have been as successful. Next in line was the biggest Chinese search engine Baidu and .. it was an another stunning fail as its shares have fallen by as much as 10% after the software was unveiled.One of the reasons for the failure is said to be the total censorship of the Chinese Internet. Seems like Chinese LLMs can‚Äôt even count to 10, just look at this, it is indeed ridiculous:\xa0https://lnkd.in/dyVB4s_NOn the contrary, the relative openness of statements in the English-speaking segment of the Internet allows you to use the LLM as a mechanism for social surveys, answering questions such as "How do you feel about government actions," you only have to give the context, such as "answer as if you were a white 30-year-old man from Oregon‚Äù. In theory, the trained model will contain a context-averaged answer.But apparently the functionality of Chinese LLMs will suffer for a long time because of censorship. #LLMs #chatgpt', '6'], ['Someone might say why a data scientist should be able to deploy code in production if ml engineers exist. Well, I think there will be a shift towards more full-stack data science roles, where individuals are expected to have a wider range of skills and knowledge.Being able to work with Jupyter Notebooks is certainly good, but sometimes you need to write a large, efficient, and beautiful python code.Recently I came across a cool resource that tells how to refactor code correctly and explains complex programming concepts in a clear way. Examples of usage in different languages, including python, are given.It is definitely worth sharing, so give it a try: https://refactoring.guru/My own code has already become much better with a use of class templates and singletones #datascientist #python #pattern', '3']]

posts: [['This year has been nothing but challenging‚Ä¶ This fact makes me even more proud to share that I‚Äôve been promoted to Strategic Planner at BBDO! Thank you to everyone, who‚Äôs been a part of this complex, yet always rewarding journey!', '37'], ['Research has always been a fundamental part of my academic and professional careers. Nowadays most of my research is aimed at finding the common ground between the use of data in marketing and consumers‚Äô digital wellbeing & privacy. Being able to present my research at the ‚ÄúLa communication √† l‚Äô√©poque de la transformation num√©rique‚Äù conference has been a great experience. My paper ‚ÄúStrategic implications of digital targeted advertising: problems of discrimination and transparency‚Äù was aimed at exploring the main challenges targeted advertising presents both for businesses and users. Data allows us, advertising industry folks, to execute amazing campaigns. Yet it‚Äôs always important to factor consumers‚Äô wellbeing in everything we do. I believe that research in cooperation with industry professionals will help us not only become more efficient for our clients but also much fairer to the consumers! Hopefully, this is just the beginning of my career path in the astonishing world of advertising üåü#BBDO #BBDOGroup #BBDOMoscow #strategicplanning #advertising", '4'], ['As 2020 is slowly approaching the end, I would like to share one great thing that happened this year. Since 2019 I and my team were slowly preparing to launch our own project. We knew that we want to help youth that is trying to make it in the creative spheres, which can seem a little scary and hard to work in (which is also true). Due to the infamous circumstances, we had to totally change the initial plans into something more accessible. And that is how ‚Äúdiapazon‚Äù was born.‚ÄúDiapazon‚Äù (directly translated from Russian as ‚Äúrange‚Äù) is a functional platform aimed at gathering support for young creative people. Our main goal is to help young creators to overcome barriers on their ways to becoming a creator. We aim to help those who are socially unprotected, facing way more obstacles in their ways.In 7 months we managed to:‚Äî help 5 youth creators to implement their creative projects ‚Äî host 2 competitions with our partner organizations (involving over 100 participants and resulting in job offers)‚Äî gain over 700 supporters on SNS Something we‚Äôre also greatly proud of is being mentioned in an article about creative hubs in the Forbes Russia article! We have recently launched the English version of our website, so feel free to visit - en.diapazonzip.com :)', '5'], ['A few days ago I was given the honor to present at the opening of the All-Russian inclusive competition for students with disabilities ‚ÄúProfessional tomorrow‚Äù alongside the representative of the Ministry of Science and Higher Education of the Russian Federation. For the past 2 years, I have been an active participant & one of the organizers of our university‚Äôs ‚ÄúResource Training and Methodological Center for the training of persons with disabilities‚Äù. Inclusive education has definitely been one of the Russian universities‚Äô main priorities for the past years. Can not wait to see what the future brings for all of us! #inclusiveeducation #inclusionmatters', '7'], ['Mina Liang and the ReneCycle, Inc. team doing some outstanding work! The future of bikesharing üôå', '2'], ['So excited to announce that I was chosen as one of the 100 youth representatives (coming from all over Russia) to participate in the leadership program aimed at connecting the best graduates of the All-Russian Forum Campaign 2020. 2020 has been as challenging as it could be, yet it was also flourishing with various opportunities. This year I managed to take part in 4 international and all-Russian forums, meeting hundreds of the most ambitious and goal-oriented students & young professionals. The forum campaign also gave me the chance to explore parts of Russia I‚Äôve never been to - learning more about the many ethnicities and cultures that are a part of our country. In the coming months all of the participants, including me, are going to go through an extensive leadership training course that will encourage us to shape the society we want to live in!More than thrilled to be a part of this program üåü', '17'], ['Throughout the last week, I was honored to attend the 46th International Conference (IC) organized by Business Today and Princeton University. #IC2020 brought together some of the most talented students from all over the world (220 students from over 60 countries) with top executives and business leaders. Guest Speaker: Marianna Simonian
Moderator: Ammar Jamshed
Date: 5th March 2023
Timings: 8:00 PM according to Pakistan time | 6:00 PM According to Moscow time

Join us for an insightful webinar on the Importance of People Analytics as the future of HR, featuring Marianna Simonian, a global people analytics leader with extensive experience in HR analytics. Marianna is also the head of the program "HR for startups" at the Higher School of Economics in Russia, and a country manager for tech and startups at Seed Group in Russia.

In this webinar, Marianna will share her expertise on the role of people analytics in shaping the future of HR, and why it's a crucial tool for any organization looking to stay ahead of the curve. Attendees will gain insights into the benefits of data-driven decision-making, and how to leverage analytics to optimize HR practices and drive business success.

LMS: www.aidatayard.com

I am not saying you shouldn‚Äôt, I personally never do. Actually there are many algorithms I never use: Logistic Regression, Naive Bayes, SVM, LDA, KNN, Feed Forward Neural Networks,... I just don‚Äôt find value in those for my work.For me the simplest model to use as a starting point for a model development is XGBoost (this includes LightGBM or Catboost as similar models). Well at least for tabular data! XGBoost natively handles missing values, categorical variables (to some extent!), it is parallelizable (so fast‚Ä¶enough), it trains on any loss function I may need, it tends to be robust to overfitting on a large number of features, and it is highly non-linear which makes it a very low bias algorithm. Its API is pretty complete, and you can achieve a lot by changing a couple of arguments. For years, I have used the same set of hyperparameters that work very well from one data set to another. I can easily throw any data into XGBoost with very little effort and this gives me a useful baseline that can drive my development from there.Here are a couple of resources to dig deeper:Github repos:- Gradient Boosting Research Papers: A curated list of gradient boosting papers with implementations: https://lnkd.in/gZQez7MG- AutoXGB: auto train XGBoost directly from CSV files, auto tune XGBoost using optuna, auto serve best XGBoost model using fastAPI: https://lnkd.in/gXPENn9s- xgboostExplainer: An R package that makes XGBoost models fully interpretable: https://lnkd.in/gUi7WJFR- XGBoostLSS: An extension of XGBoost for probabilistic forecasting: https://lnkd.in/gk8BP3ZY- Data-Science-Competitions: The goal of this repo is to provide the solutions to all Data Science Competitions (Kaggle, Data Hack, Machine Hack, Driven Data etc...): https://lnkd.in/ge9Hfpz5Similar models:- LightGBM: LightGBM is a gradient boosting framework that uses tree-based learning algorithms. If you then ask for more details, they will probably give you some vague explanations revolving around the different costs that these metrics attribute to errors (False Positives and False Negatives). But what are ùó≤ùòÖùóÆùó∞ùòÅùóπùòÜ these costs?In my latest Towards Data Science article, I delved into this topic and showed how these metrics can be decomposed (or approximated, in the case of the F1-score) as the product of each element of the confusion matrix with its value (or cost).Moreover, following this approach, it is possible to easily define your own metric, depending on how much each correct (wrong) prediction is worth (costs). In the image below, you can see an example of how the optimal number of observations predicted as positives changes depending on the value attached to TP, FP, TN, and FN. This custom metric has a ùó±ùó∂ùóøùó≤ùó∞ùòÅ ùó≤ùó∞ùóºùóªùóºùó∫ùó∂ùó∞ ùó∂ùóªùòÅùó≤ùóøùóΩùóøùó≤ùòÅùóÆùòÅùó∂ùóºùóª, so it's much better for taking business decisions. It wouldn't have been possible without the support of my colleagues, relatives and friends.#bp #oilandgas #production", '256'], ['Happy 10 years, Baku Higher Oil School! üá¶üáøI‚Äôm proud to be a part of this family! üéì#BHOS #BANM #10years', '42'], ['#Oilplatform #Construction #Challenges Although power supply of most oil platforms is fulfilled by diesel generators, Shell has designed its Appomattox oil platform fully electric by driving idea from Tesla in order to be more environmentally friendly and mitigate emission impacts.To provide required amount of electricity an idea of using natural gas and steam turbines put forward, but in this case huge amount of water was needed for cooling. They figured out that 2.5 million barrels sea water per day was needed for achievement of this process which was equal to Houston\'s potable water supply every day.The biggest challenge they faced was that by using less water they had to kept marine life uninfluenced. After the involvement of marine researchers it becomes apparent that water at the depth of 2000 feet was so much colder that enabled to halve the consumption. However, another challenge came across that in this depth of water small marine creatures called as "Phronima" lives.
